images.caption: Yolanda Griffith is just a 3-pointer away from 3,000 points.

article.linkText: Powell, Walker pace Monarchs' rout of Lynx
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- The Sacramento Monarchs shut down Katie Smith and improved their franchise-best start. Nicole Powell scored 18 points and the Monarchs limited Smith, the league's leading scorer, to just three points in a 67-50 victory over the Minnesota Lynx on Friday night. Smith, averaging 20.3 points, made just 1-of-5 shots -- a 3-pointer early in the game -- and attempted just one field goal in the second half. "I didn't realize that she had [only] three points until after the game," Powell said. "That's huge. She's an unbelievable player. We played great team defense." DeMya Walker had 14 points and eight rebounds for Western Conference-leading Sacramento (8-2), which won for the fifth time in six games. Yolanda Griffith had 12 points and Rebekkah Brunson added 10. "That was a good win against the team that was the closest to us [in the standings]," Sacramento coach John Whisenant said. "They are a good shooting team and a good rebounding team. We pushed them out of their offense. We feel our defense creates turnovers and gives us an opportunity to win." Svetlana Abrosimova had 13 points and nine rebounds for Minnesota (5-4), which had won four straight games. It was the Lynx's scoring total of the season, and the lowest by a Monarchs' opponent.

"We pretty much just got outplayed," Minnesota center Nicole Ohlde said. "Sacramento was aggressive early and we just didn't respond." Griffith, averaging 16.4 points this season, fell three short of becoming the seventh player in WNBA history to reach 3,000 for her career. Powell shot 7-for-12 from field, mostly on the perimeter, and added four rebounds and three steals. "I got a lot of good passes and good looks tonight," Powell said. "In the second half I was trying to be more aggressive and was getting some close-range jumpers." Sacramento, which led 39-25 at halftime, used a 21-4 run in the first half to take a 20-point lead midway through the opening period and held a double-digit advantage for most of the rest of the game.
